Based on the retrieved evidence, my agreement remains unchanged. Extensive cross-linking of blood clots is indeed performed by Factor XIII, as evidenced again in detail across many references including [2], [6], and others. Thrombin initiates the clot formation process by converting fibrinogen to fibrin, but Factor XIII is responsible for the critical step of crosslinking the fibrin fibers together to ensure the clot's structural strength and stability. Without Factor XIII performing this extensive cross-linking, even though thrombin has created the basic structure of the clot, it wouldn't remain structurally sound enough for proper hemostasis or wound healing functions. Therefore, my stance aligns precisely with option D: \boxed{D}
